WEBVTT

1
00:02:39.160 --> 00:02:40.870
Mrs Peterson!

2
00:02:41.037 --> 00:02:43.498
Ramon, hey! How's it going?

3
00:02:43.581 --> 00:02:45.083
How you doing?

4
00:02:46.167 --> 00:02:48.086
There it is, there on the desk.

5
00:02:48.169 --> 00:02:49.879
Where's she headed?

6
00:02:49.963 --> 00:02:51.589
She's snowbound, Ramon.

7
00:02:55.510 --> 00:02:57.095
See you went with the pink.

8
00:02:57.178 --> 00:03:00.473
Yeah, yeah. It's kind of a pink day today.

9
00:03:01.266 --> 00:03:03.518
I'll have another pickup for you on Thursday.

10
00:03:03.601 --> 00:03:06.187
- All right. See you then.
- All right. Thanks.

11
00:03:41.472 --> 00:03:43.558
Peterson! Peterson!

12
00:03:44.726 --> 00:03:45.852
Peterson.

13
00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:51.941
- Mr Cowboy, <i>da?
- Da.</i>

14
00:03:57.196 --> 00:03:58.656
It's pretty.

15
00:04:01.743 --> 00:04:03.411
It's from my wife.

16
00:05:10.478 --> 00:05:13.898
Time rules over us without mercy,

17
00:05:13.982 --> 00:05:17.902
not caring if we're healthy or ill, hungry or drunk,

18
00:05:17.986 --> 00:05:21.364
Russian, American, beings from Mars.

19
00:05:21.447 --> 00:05:24.659
It's like a fire. It could either destroy us
or keep us warm.

20
00:05:24.742 --> 00:05:27.245
That's why every FedEx office has a clock.

21
00:05:27.328 --> 00:05:30.081
Because we live or we die by the clock.

22
00:05:30.164 --> 00:05:31.916
We never turn our back on it.

23
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:37.088
And we never, ever allow ourselves
the sin of losing track of time!

24
00:05:37.755 --> 00:05:39.924
Locally, it's 1:56.

25
00:05:40.008 --> 00:05:43.803
That means we've got three hours and four minutes

26
00:05:43.886 --> 00:05:45.722
before the end-of-the-day's
package sort.

27
00:05:45.805 --> 00:05:49.350
That's how long we have.
That's how much time we have

28
00:05:50.268 --> 00:05:53.104
before this pulsating, accursed, relentless taskmaster

29
00:05:53.229 --> 00:05:55.606
tries to put us out of business.

30
00:05:56.315 --> 00:05:59.027
Hey, Nicolai. Good to see you.

31
00:05:59.110 --> 00:06:00.778
How are you, kid?

32
00:06:00.862 --> 00:06:03.197
You just delivered your very first FedEx package.

33
00:06:03.281 --> 00:06:05.366
That deserves something special,

34
00:06:05.450 --> 00:06:09.287
like a Snickers bar and a CD player.

35
00:06:09.746 --> 00:06:12.874
And something to listen to.
There. Elvis Presley.

36
00:06:12.957 --> 00:06:14.709
Fifty million fans can't be wrong.

37
00:06:14.792 --> 00:06:16.627
You all recognise this, don't you?

38
00:06:16.711 --> 00:06:19.547
I took the liberty of sending this to myself.

39
00:06:19.630 --> 00:06:24.135
I FedEx'd it before I left Memphis.

40
00:06:24.385 --> 00:06:26.763
You're probably wondering what could be in here.

41
00:06:26.846 --> 00:06:30.933
Is it architectural plans?
Maybe technical drawings?

42
00:06:31.142 --> 00:06:34.520
Is this the new wallpaper for the bathroom?

43
00:06:36.022 --> 00:06:38.691
It is a clock,

44
00:06:39.233 --> 00:06:40.568
which I started at absolute zero,

45
00:06:40.651 --> 00:06:44.864
and is now at 87 hours, 22 minutes and 17 seconds.

46
00:06:46.032 --> 00:06:50.161
From Memphis, America, to Nicolai in Russia, 87 hours.

47
00:06:50.953 --> 00:06:54.373
Eighty-seven hours
is a shameful outrage.

48
00:06:54.457 --> 00:06:56.834
This is just an egg timer!

49
00:06:57.335 --> 00:07:00.254
What if it had been something else?
Like your paycheque?

50
00:07:00.338 --> 00:07:03.341
Or fresh boysenberries?
Or adoption papers?

51
00:07:03.674 --> 00:07:05.384
Eighty-seven hours is an eternity.

52
00:07:05.468 --> 00:07:07.512
The cosmos was created in less time!

53
00:07:07.595 --> 00:07:10.431
Wars have been fought and nations toppled in 87 hours!

54
00:07:10.515 --> 00:07:12.850
Fortunes made and squandered.

55
00:07:17.563 --> 00:07:20.358
What? What are you saying about me?

56
00:07:20.441 --> 00:07:21.943
I tell them, what do they expect?

57
00:07:22.026 --> 00:07:26.280
This man, when his truck broke down,
he stole a boy's bicycle.

58
00:07:26.364 --> 00:07:29.075
I borrowed it! I borrowed a kid's bike.

59
00:07:29.158 --> 00:07:32.620
I got my packages delivered,
and that is what you have to do.

60
00:07:32.703 --> 00:07:33.955
You have to do whatever it takes,

61
00:07:34.038 --> 00:07:36.040
because in three hours and two minutes

62
00:07:36.124 --> 00:07:39.418
every one of these packages has to be on the big truck,

63
00:07:39.502 --> 00:07:41.170
on its way to the airport.

64
00:07:42.255 --> 00:07:43.798
Fifteen minutes!

65
00:07:43.881 --> 00:07:47.051
- Crunch time! Crunch time!
- Crunch time!

66
00:07:47.218 --> 00:07:50.471
Let's go! Every package
on the airport truck.

67
00:07:50.555 --> 00:07:52.723
Go! Crunch, crunch, crunch!

68
00:07:52.807 --> 00:07:54.559
- We have a big problem.
- What?

69
00:07:54.642 --> 00:07:57.436
- The truck in Red Square is stuck.
- What?

70
00:07:57.520 --> 00:08:00.148
- It's stuck.
- Stuck how? In snow? In ice?

71
00:08:00.231 --> 00:08:03.734
The most important truck,
the Kremlin truck! Many packages.

72
00:08:13.911 --> 00:08:18.166
All right. Let's put the table right here.
We'll just do the sort.

73
00:08:18.249 --> 00:08:21.002
Yeah, a clamp.
That would make us stuck.

74
00:08:21.460 --> 00:08:23.838
Let's go. Unload... Get him out of there.

75
00:08:23.921 --> 00:08:26.674
Right here. Two lines, two lines.

76
00:08:26.757 --> 00:08:29.594
One to the airport truck, one to the Moscow truck.

77
00:08:29.677 --> 00:08:30.887
Got it?

78
00:08:31.304 --> 00:08:34.140
CDG, FE, ME, Memphis on the airport truck.

79
00:08:34.223 --> 00:08:37.602
Everything else there. Nicolai!
Tick-tock, tick-tock. Four minutes.

80
00:08:40.479 --> 00:08:42.815
<i>Hi, this is Kelly.
If you're calling for Chuck, press one.</i>

81
00:08:42.899 --> 00:08:45.401
<i>Otherwise, leave a message. Thanks.</i>

82
00:08:46.110 --> 00:08:48.988
<i>Kelly. Are you there?
Pick up, pick up, pick up.</i>

83
00:08:49.071 --> 00:08:51.032
<i>You're not there.</i>

84
00:08:51.115 --> 00:08:55.411
<i>I'm doing the sorts in Red Square,
in the shadow of Lenin's tomb.</i>

85
00:08:55.494 --> 00:08:56.746
<i>I miss you.</i>

86
00:08:56.871 --> 00:08:58.873
I miss you, I really wanna kiss you.

87
00:08:58.956 --> 00:09:01.834
I'm picking up the sweep through Paris.

88
00:09:01.918 --> 00:09:04.462
I should be back in Memphis in about 18 hours.

89
00:09:04.545 --> 00:09:05.838
That's the good news.

90
00:09:05.922 --> 00:09:08.674
The bad news is... I gotta go to the dentist this week.

91
00:09:08.758 --> 00:09:10.218
I got something that's hurting.

92
00:09:10.301 --> 00:09:13.554
I'll see you soon, and you know what that means.

93
00:09:13.638 --> 00:09:16.307
Bye-bye. Nicolai!
Tick-tock, tick-tock, tick-tock!

94
00:09:34.575 --> 00:09:37.870
I absolutely, positively have to get to Memphis tonight.

95
00:09:37.954 --> 00:09:39.914
Can't help you. Try UPS.

96
00:09:39.997 --> 00:09:42.959
Will we be able to push it and make the sort?

97
00:09:43.042 --> 00:09:45.086
- We'll do our best.
- "Our best"?

98
00:09:45.169 --> 00:09:49.131
Gwen, what's wrong with our doctors
that Jack is certified to fly?

99
00:09:49.674 --> 00:09:51.133
Aren't you concerned?

100
00:09:51.217 --> 00:09:53.803
Terrified, but a girl's gotta do what a girl's gotta do.

101
00:09:53.886 --> 00:09:56.931
That's the spirit. Relentless is our goal.

102
00:09:57.014 --> 00:10:01.394
What do you expect from the guy
who stole a crippled kid's bicycle?

103
00:10:01.477 --> 00:10:04.855
I borrowed it.
But I love that the kid's now crippled.

104
00:10:05.189 --> 00:10:07.441
So you missed the last truck by two minutes?

105
00:10:07.525 --> 00:10:10.027
Two minutes. Actually, it was less.

106
00:10:10.653 --> 00:10:13.572
The plane wasn't heavy.
You could've added some fuel

107
00:10:13.656 --> 00:10:15.825
and picked up speed.

108
00:10:15.908 --> 00:10:18.703
It's about the trucks.
Today's truck was two minutes late.

109
00:10:18.786 --> 00:10:21.747
Tomorrow's will be four minutes late, then six, eight.

110
00:10:21.831 --> 00:10:24.500
Next thing you know, we're the US Mail.

111
00:10:24.583 --> 00:10:26.961
Well, all I'm saying is,

112
00:10:27.044 --> 00:10:28.421
if you'd gotten all those trucks on the plane,

113
00:10:28.504 --> 00:10:31.257
those Russkies would be walking on water now.

114
00:10:31.340 --> 00:10:35.052
Hey, don't give me that look.
It's just grape juice.

115
00:10:35.136 --> 00:10:36.429
- Right, Chuck?
- Yeah.

116
00:10:36.512 --> 00:10:39.390
Yeah. It's like
a 1992 full-bodied grape juice.

117
00:10:39.473 --> 00:10:41.767
See no evil, hear no evil, speak no evil.

118
00:10:41.851 --> 00:10:44.979
We'd offer you some, but somebody's got to fly the plane.

119
00:10:45.062 --> 00:10:47.565
Yeah, well, I "just say no," right?

120
00:10:48.941 --> 00:10:52.737
Listen, Stan, I've been meaning to ask you, how's Mary?

121
00:10:55.239 --> 00:10:56.449
Well...

122
00:10:57.283 --> 00:10:59.744
We really don't know anything yet.

123
00:11:00.953 --> 00:11:03.831
She went to the doctor yesterday, and...

124
00:11:05.583 --> 00:11:08.753
It hasn't metastasized

125
00:11:09.253 --> 00:11:11.756
as far as they can tell right now.

126
00:11:12.590 --> 00:11:14.925
It's just kind of wait and see.

127
00:11:15.301 --> 00:11:16.761
I'm so sorry.

128
00:11:17.595 --> 00:11:20.806
Tell her I'm gonna come by
and see her on my next layover.

129
00:11:20.890 --> 00:11:24.226
I want you to know, Stan,
we are all thinking about her and you,

130
00:11:24.310 --> 00:11:27.271
- and just blessings.
- Thank you, Gwen.

131
00:11:27.355 --> 00:11:29.482
<i>Hi, this is Kelly.
If you're calling for Chuck, press one.</i>

132
00:11:29.565 --> 00:11:32.234
<i>Otherwise, leave a message.</i>

133
00:11:37.907 --> 00:11:39.116
Stan...

134
00:11:40.659 --> 00:11:42.912
Listen. I heard about this...

135
00:11:45.081 --> 00:11:48.376
I heard about this doctor down in Emory, in Atlanta.

136
00:11:48.626 --> 00:11:52.380
He's supposed to be the best.
He worked on Frank Toretto's wife.

137
00:11:52.463 --> 00:11:56.384
Frank's a systems analyst.
He played centerfield for us.

138
00:11:56.467 --> 00:11:59.637
You know him. The softball tournament
last Labour Day.

139
00:11:59.720 --> 00:12:01.722
Anyway, beside the point.

140
00:12:02.431 --> 00:12:06.018
What I was thinking is, is that I could get his number,

141
00:12:06.310 --> 00:12:08.145
the doctor, and...

142
00:12:09.146 --> 00:12:11.732
You know, put you all together and...

143
00:12:13.067 --> 00:12:16.821
You know, you could get this thing fixed.
You could beat it.

144
00:12:18.781 --> 00:12:20.282
Thanks, Chuck.

145
00:12:21.117 --> 00:12:23.035
So, I'll get his number.

146
00:12:30.126 --> 00:12:33.379
- And why is that?
- When it's chemically ordered...

147
00:12:45.724 --> 00:12:49.353
- Is Kelly Frears around?
- She's copying her dissertation.

148
00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:23.512
- You're home.
- Home indeed.

149
00:13:23.596 --> 00:13:25.556
I love that you're home.

150
00:13:44.909 --> 00:13:48.579
<i>Just days before Santa departs
on his annual gift-giving venture,</i>

151
00:13:48.662 --> 00:13:51.415
<i>he's been declared physically fit to fly.</i>

152
00:13:51.582 --> 00:13:55.503
<i>Santa got checked out at the
VA Hospital in Augusta, Georgia.</i>

153
00:13:55.586 --> 00:13:58.255
<i>After doctors declared the jolly old elf in tiptop shape,</i>

154
00:13:58.339 --> 00:14:01.926
<i>Santa took off into the wild blue yonder
for an early start.</i>

155
00:14:02.051 --> 00:14:04.595
<i>In Sarajevo, he spent the day with children,</i>

156
00:14:04.762 --> 00:14:07.264
<i>handing out presents and even helping them decorate</i>

157
00:14:07.348 --> 00:14:09.433
<i>the special Christmas tree.</i>

158
00:14:13.812 --> 00:14:18.025
<i>Santa and elves took over the floor
at the Hong Kong Futures Exchange.</i>

159
00:14:18.150 --> 00:14:20.778
<i>Market traders bought Santa hats...</i>

160
00:14:43.425 --> 00:14:47.638
- The turkey's a bit dry, isn't it?
- No. The turkey is perfect!

161
00:14:51.559 --> 00:14:54.770
- How many did you do last night?
- Last night? 2.9 million.

162
00:14:54.853 --> 00:14:58.816
Now, you've got to be in the market
for more of these candied yams.

163
00:15:00.150 --> 00:15:02.486
2.9 has got to be the record.

164
00:15:02.611 --> 00:15:03.988
Look at those marshmallows.

165
00:15:04.989 --> 00:15:08.325
- We thought two million was a big deal.
- The glory days.

166
00:15:08.409 --> 00:15:11.370
- What'd they do the first night?
- First night?

167
00:15:11.579 --> 00:15:13.330
- Twelve.
- Twelve thousand?

168
00:15:13.581 --> 00:15:15.958
- Hell, no. Twelve.
- That's right.

169
00:15:16.041 --> 00:15:18.252
They did the sort right there on a card table.

170
00:15:18.335 --> 00:15:21.463
And Fred Smith had that card table bronzed.

171
00:15:21.880 --> 00:15:24.091
I've been hearing that for five years.

172
00:15:24.174 --> 00:15:28.304
- It's in his office today.
- From that to the hub at Anchorage.

173
00:15:28.387 --> 00:15:32.474
It's a perfect marriage between
technology and systems management.

174
00:15:33.642 --> 00:15:38.022
Speaking of marriage, when are you
gonna make an honest woman of Kelly?

175
00:15:38.689 --> 00:15:41.900
- How long?
- Fourteen minutes into the meal.

176
00:15:42.026 --> 00:15:44.028
You won. I owe you five.

177
00:15:44.194 --> 00:15:46.697
- Way before the pie.
- I told him.

178
00:15:46.989 --> 00:15:49.950
Right about the time the pie came out, the marriage...

179
00:15:50.075 --> 00:15:53.078
Kelly's still recovering after that parolee.

180
00:15:53.579 --> 00:15:55.289
He was a lawyer.

181
00:15:55.664 --> 00:15:59.335
I knew it had something to do
with swearing to tell the truth.

182
00:15:59.418 --> 00:16:02.838
Remember when he fell and broke
his shoulder at the wedding reception?

183
00:16:02.963 --> 00:16:05.716
He tripped on a kerb holding a door open for me.

184
00:16:06.300 --> 00:16:09.595
- Aunt Kelly was married?
- It's not worth remembering.

185
00:16:09.720 --> 00:16:12.056
So since her failed marriage to the parolee...

186
00:16:12.556 --> 00:16:13.891
Oh, my God.

187
00:16:14.016 --> 00:16:17.102
Kelly can't see being with a man
who wears a pager to bed.

188
00:16:17.227 --> 00:16:19.146
What are you gonna attach it to?

189
00:16:19.647 --> 00:16:22.107
When you wear it to bed,
I hope you got one of those things

190
00:16:22.191 --> 00:16:23.942
that goes vibrating.

191
00:16:25.361 --> 00:16:27.279
I'm not touching that.

192
00:16:27.905 --> 00:16:29.990
Oh, did you hit an olive pit?

193
00:16:30.074 --> 00:16:33.702
- I thought I took all of them out.
- No, no, it's not that.

194
00:17:00.771 --> 00:17:03.148
- Okay, I'll cancel Saturday.
- No, don't.

195
00:17:03.273 --> 00:17:05.859
If I'm not here, I'm not.
But if I am, then I am.

196
00:17:05.943 --> 00:17:08.696
It's cancelled.
But you gotta be here New Year's Eve.

197
00:17:08.779 --> 00:17:11.281
Malaysia can't be that bad.

198
00:17:11.365 --> 00:17:14.034
- When do you defend your dissertation?
- January 12.

199
00:17:16.078 --> 00:17:18.539
I'm gonna have to switch over the South America thing.

200
00:17:18.622 --> 00:17:21.125
If I do that on the third or fourth,

201
00:17:21.208 --> 00:17:22.918
I'll have to head back out on the 13th.

202
00:17:23.001 --> 00:17:24.962
So long as you're here New Year's Eve.

203
00:17:25.045 --> 00:17:27.840
I will be here New Year's Eve. I promise.

204
00:17:32.052 --> 00:17:33.053
What?

205
00:17:33.721 --> 00:17:35.973
What about our Christmas?
I got a gift for you.

206
00:17:39.601 --> 00:17:41.061
We have to do it in the car.

207
00:17:46.442 --> 00:17:49.820
I'd just like a minute over here,
all right? Thanks.

208
00:17:57.286 --> 00:18:01.081
Two minutes, okay? Two more minutes.
Thanks. Hey!

209
00:18:01.165 --> 00:18:04.251
- Merry Christmas.
- I thought you were gonna stiff me.

210
00:18:04.334 --> 00:18:05.586
What is the ribbon?

211
00:18:05.669 --> 00:18:08.797
A thousand-pound test fishing line
or something?

212
00:18:08.881 --> 00:18:11.258
- Here's your fancy thing.
- Thanks.

213
00:18:15.679 --> 00:18:17.514
I love the wrapping.

214
00:18:19.516 --> 00:18:21.477
- And I love the box.
- Good.

215
00:18:27.107 --> 00:18:30.569
Oh, my. Oh, that is terrific.

216
00:18:31.695 --> 00:18:33.864
My granddaddy used it on the Southern Pacific.

217
00:18:36.700 --> 00:18:40.162
Hey, I took this.
This is my favourite picture of you.

218
00:18:42.372 --> 00:18:43.707
You know what I'm gonna do?

219
00:18:43.791 --> 00:18:46.919
I'm always gonna keep this on Memphis time.

220
00:18:51.507 --> 00:18:52.716
Kelly time.

221
00:18:54.301 --> 00:18:56.804
You haven't said anything about your presents.

222
00:18:56.887 --> 00:19:00.182
I'm sorry. No, I love them.
Look at my journal.

223
00:19:01.308 --> 00:19:05.103
- What about the pager?
- Real leather. Gold on the pages!

224
00:19:05.312 --> 00:19:08.106
- Did you like the pager or not?
- Yes. I love it.

225
00:19:08.190 --> 00:19:11.068
Look at him in his little blue Russian house.

226
00:19:11.235 --> 00:19:12.986
- It's from Russia.
- My God.

227
00:19:13.737 --> 00:19:15.948
- It's not one of those loud ones?
- No.

228
00:19:16.031 --> 00:19:20.244
You can program it so it vibrates
and lights up and see it in the dark.

229
00:19:20.744 --> 00:19:23.205
It seems like a real nice... pager.

230
00:19:24.581 --> 00:19:27.209
- Sorry about the towels.
- I love them!

231
00:19:27.292 --> 00:19:29.628
- You're hard to shop for.
- Every time I wash my hands,

232
00:19:29.753 --> 00:19:32.256
- I will think of you.
- All right, I gotta go.

233
00:19:33.215 --> 00:19:34.883
Merry Christmas.

234
00:19:35.467 --> 00:19:36.844
- Merry Christmas.
- I love you.

235
00:19:36.927 --> 00:19:38.470
I love you, too.

236
00:19:45.894 --> 00:19:47.104
Chuck!

237
00:19:47.521 --> 00:19:48.605
Keys!

238
00:19:58.699 --> 00:20:01.493
- Thank you.
- That reminds me. I almost forgot.

239
00:20:01.577 --> 00:20:03.912
I have one more present for you.

240
00:20:05.455 --> 00:20:09.459
